interactions.feelings: And if I may say more about the Marimekko shirt, so I have always wondered what’s the deal with those shirts, because they are pretty ugly to me. But very popular. And I had one coworker who always wore Marimekko shirts at work in the office. There was no uniform, nothing, but always a Marimekko shirt. He/she had several of them, in different colors. And it was, it was always thought, that Lisse, the one who wears those Marimekko shirts. And so it was. These were my memories of these shirts, that’s all I can say.

This is the wish that I have, for my part.

interactions.feelings: At least one of the memories related to that gas canister is when we were at the cabin. And when we left, we were at least chatting and such, and it was quite a calm moment. Mother's gas canister was in the trunk. There was the smell of gasoline. The car hummed nicely, it did make a nice sound. It wasn't exactly the quietest car, but it still produced a nice sound. At least it had an interesting humming sound of the engine. A whistling sound, the sound of a small radio. It was a nice time.

interactions.feelings: Well, here we continue about this Pastille. This colour is absolutely magnificent to me, I can't tell whether this picture reproduces its colour correctly, but hopefully it does, the correct colour of the chair, and it, and I like that colour and then I like the asymmetry in it, that’s probably partly because of the angle of view. This is somehow, doesn’t this, doesn’t this rock somehow, nicely, so that it’s like rockable. With this chair, rocking is allowed.

And now when I look at it with today's eyes, I see in it a pretty beautifully crafted object, which is, which has a lot of such features that are not, that attach it to the design of the 1950s and 1960s. It has clear features, the chosen material is of high quality and, and this design. It is made of durable, strong metal. The colors have been carefully chosen, it has blue and white, Finnish colors, and then a little bit of red has been put in.

interactions.feelings: That is by no means a grandma cup to me, since it was like my parents' normal coffee cup. And they had some that were brown-edged, and then later purchased some that were gold-edged. And now, of course, I have them in the cupboard, but I don’t use the ones with flowers on them. But I have a lot of them as a white version. And its goodness is based on the fact, that coffee tastes better when drunk from a cup with a thin edge, than when drunk from a mug. And then the handle is terribly good to hold in your hand. So, it is kind of like ergonomic, whether you like the form of it or not. But yes, it works well as a coffee cup.

interactions.feelings: Eero Aarnio's chair Pastille represents to me one of the top products in Finnish design and these successful objects of the 1960s. Looking from today, from this angle, it is a bit of a controversial era and product, when plastic made its breakthrough in various products and designs. There was not so much concern for responsibility, and there was no talk of ecological material or such, but one went firmly forward and plastic represented modernism and, and a material which was very suitable for production in many ways. And even before, before the energy crises and so on.

interactions.feelings: I am Kaarina and a very big friend of these looms. There were many years inbetween, but now I started again from the beginning. And it has indeed been difficult, as there are four pedals, and the warps are black, to make a rug called Kirkonkaari. So someone can come practice with me, I can teach the making of it now too. But I unraveled and wound many times. But I hope there would be more of these weavers there. And in Töyrytie 4 there is a weaving place, so one can come and see them. And we have had a couple of men learning there, and the boys have done the weaving well too.

interactions.feelings: And I have a few memories of this Savonia series, I still have some of them. I got the first ones myself, and the next ones we got as a wedding gift in 1973. And a it’s a good, functional series.

And what's special about this, is this wooden handle that can be used to lift the cover comfortably. One won’t, one won’t burn their fingers. This iron pot in the picture is red. Here it is enamelled white on the inside. It probably doesn’t interfere with the functionality of the pot, but I personally like that original black iron pot. And as I’ve said before, it’s absolutely wonderful compared to a regular frying pan. It doesn’t spill the fats because it has high edges. But every time I use my own pot, I have used it many times this year, too, always, immediately after use, I wash it with hot water and a dish brush, by no means soap. With hot water and a brush, and then I put oil on it right away. And because of that, it's always in good condition.

I have a memory of a moped in the sense that, when I practiced with that moped, my brother did tell me how to start it, but he didn't remember to say how to stop it. And then it was on a narrow road, so a willow bush was what stopped it.

interactions.feelings: I'm Marke, and I chose a rug like this. And I checked from behind there, and saw that it is made by Ritva Puotila, from The Friends of Finnish Handicraft. When my parents died, they had ordered a big blue rug from her, which of course no one wanted to take. And then I took it to The Finnish White Ribbon Union. And they fell in love with it, one could see that. And they took it to the laundry. And there it is, hangs on their wall.

Then my aunt died, and she also had two rugs. Then no one wanted those either, because nowadays the apartments are so low, and they require a higher, three, four meter apartment. And then I took it there again, to the Finnish White Ribbon Union on Liisankatu. There they hang, washed and beautiful. But rugs don’t really fit into these modern apartments.

interactions.feelings: I myself have a rug woven by my late mother, “Muisto Karjalasta”. By Norma Heimola. It was made in the 1970s. And she had this situation in the 1950s, after being evacuated, that with the wives of her uncles, they used this kind of material, dismantled felt from a paper machine. The felt from the paper machine was dismantled into yarn and dyed with dyes from plants. So this rug I now have in my archives, I’m wondering where should one put it. It dates from 1952, 1953. And its model is “Itämaan tietäjät”, or something like that, you can find it in the rug catalogs. And how skilfully these women have made decorations and embellishments for themselves, then after the war.

Savonia is familiar to me too, but next I will take the Jokapoika shirt. I have boys and men in my family. And then I decided that for each one of them, I will buy a Jokapoika shirt at some point. And it was pretty interesting that, some of them wanted to use it, but then there was a phase where they said, I certainly won’t be wearing that one, I’m not a boy that wears Marimekko. And that it’s a shirt for a girlish boy. But now, in recent years, the same boys that are now in their fifties, have wanted to look back, and look for the shirt from the attic of the cottage, and put it on. Quite clearly. And it's a durable shirt. You can almost say that it goes from father to son.

And now let’s have some memories of this Jopo. So I am Eeva-Kaarina. And Jopo brings to my mind that, while growing up with siblings, I always inherited bicycles from my big sisters. And then I was probably already working for the summer, as a swimming instructor. And the Jopo bicycles had just entered the market. And I dreamed that with the money I earned from the job, I would buy a Jopo. And that Jopo was the same kind of orange colour as this one. And it was wonderful that I had my own bicycle  for the first time. It was approximately at the turn of the 1970s. Yeah, 1975 it says here. Well yeah, I remembered pretty well. Well, what's your next object, Leena.

And now my moped there, the Tunturi moped, reminded me of a trip. So, I could go to get those Myrnas back to Finland, so that the big sister's sons could also inherit these cups. Personally, I didn’t want these because they always have to be washed by hand. Yeah.

You will not take one? Well, for me, the Pastille chair. It’s Eero's chair, from the 1960s. And at some point I had a dream and a wish that I could get this, but when I tried it in some expositions and exhibitions, it was very difficult to sit in it. And then that plastic surface was like, it like gave me a sweaty feeling. So no, not nice, not good. And, but it's beautiful, and it's interesting, and the kids surely love it, and on some terrace of a summer cottage it's a most splendid object.

And when you think of the whole heritage of Finnish rugs, so, well, it has been a terribly diverse textile.

interactions.feelings: In this picture there is a moped from the 1960s. And this reminded me of that the first motor vehicle I bought for myself was Solifer, but not this model, it was the Speed model. But this design clearly reminds me of that it is quite the same as Tunturi, Pappatunturi, which is a collecting rarity.

interactions.feelings: And it has been a significant object at celebrations. When there has been an important, important event in the family, and a celebration space, then the Myrnas have been brought into use, and they have like given that celebration its own glory and place of honor.

Now I remember. There was this Klaus Järvinen, a musician. And he wore these Jokapoika shirts. He appeared pretty often in television in the 1960s and 1970s. It was kind of like his uniform, that Jokapoika shirt. They are beautiful, they are stunning. And well, I would have always wanted one like that for myself, but well… They are a little bit like more masculine.
Gray, smoke gray. A spring comes to mind, a spring in the forest, from this Aalto vase. Personally, I'm absolutely crazy about Aalto vases.

And this chair by Eero Aarnio. It is charming. It has lovely shapes. And there comes the lights and the colours, and so on. And someone says this is a useless object. I think this is… As I told before here, sailing on the waves of the lake with this one was a lot of fun, also for an adult.

And I'll start with this rug. There are very many such elements here, that can be seen in folk art. And on the other hand, there are absolutely lovely shades of like, ochre, gray and purple. I could have imagined that this would be older production than 1975. But well, quite spectacular and beautiful and gorgeous.

Well, there is this Solifer moped here, which is extremely streamlined. It looks a bit like it could be from France. I don't know which country does it come from, one can see that it has/is bensoo (?). So it's probably either Yankee or English. But it’s very beautiful. It must have given great success while courting.

Three-legged Aalto stool, by Alvar Aalto, from the collections of Artek. We had these at home. My parents had bought some of these in the 1950s, these Aalto products, after they got married. So they had received some money as a present, and we had these at home. As a little girl, I kept falling on the floor with it, and I thought it was pretty dangerous and rickety. But when you deal with it properly, it is extremely comfortable.

interactions.feelings: Well then, another thing we thought of, started to think of, was that, it says here everywhere, that is this, this is a jerrycan. So, we all thought that a jerrycan is kind of like metallic, angular, not this much designed, like made of tin, like a gas canister. And, the guide in our table said as well, that it does say jerry here, but it doesn’t say that, I think it quite clearly says VR here. And then I can’t see what the smaller text says, Orthex maybe or some year or something, so it doesn’t say jerry, so is jerry then more like a generic name for a can, a name one can use, or is a jerrycan really the one made of tin, and this is actually like a plastic canister. And Eero Rislakki has designed this, so VR can’t mean that either, his initials, but well, in any case this is a picture that brings me warm associations and the colour of the red can is lovely too, and well, that’s why I wanted to talk about this one.

interactions.feelings: And I chose this Jerry canister because there may have been juice, water, and gasoline in it. All of these. And we used to have a boat, and there was water in it then. So when one is on an island or something like that, there may not always be a well there. So it has been used as a water jug then. So that's why I took this Jerry canister. That’s the memory it brought up.

interactions.feelings: They really were with us for a long time, but now they have passed on to the next generation. Both boys got one of these Pastille chairs to their own home, and at one boy’s home it was said to be the most expensive piece of furniture in the family. But the chair has brought joy also to their daughter.

interactions.feelings: Okay. So this is Eero Aarnio's Pastille chair, which I don't have like actual personal experience of, like from home, but my friend has this chair. And I have tested sitting on it, and I think it’s more beautiful as an object than for sitting, but well, I think it’s a very elegant, elegant object.

In this picture is a moped named Solifer that takes my thoughts to the 1960s countryside where I lived and grew up before I left away from there. And this kind of a moped was a pretty common vehicle there, especially for slightly older men, apparently for such men who didn't buy a car, but maybe they couldn’t afford it either, and they anyway needed some ride, and this product was then purchased for the family and it was used quite diligently too.

interactions.feelings: I wonder what kind of a tree would like to sit on this very chair. It would be so firm and noble, that one would have to bury the feet in the deep sand of the most beautiful beach.

interactions.feelings: To the best of my recollection, I indeed fell off this high chair as a child. Later, I have thought that I must have been a bit too old for that chair and a bit too wild. And that's probably the reason why I fell and got some sort of concussion. There were more concussions afterwards too, though. That's it.
